@Nobis Miserere In my experience, people mostly say "whom" a little ironically, like they are trying to convey "I know I sound pretentious now".

As a speaker of Slovenian with its six cases and three grammatical numbers and ten different declension patterns, I always found the subject-object distinction for some pronouns in English (I-me, who-whom) super easy. And it's interesting to see native speakers struggle with those.

A good example is the incorrect "between you and I" that I hear quite often. It sounds weird to native speakers, but they still sometimes use it when trying to speak formally. I think the reason is that they know that "it is I" and "the only people there were she and I" are correct-but-weird, and they assume that "between you and I" falls in the same category.
